Chest X-Ray: you can go to this center for a chest x-ray. We are going to see if there are infections, fluids, or masses in your lungs.
CT chest: I am sending you for a CT of your chest because your medical history requires a more comprehensive look at your chest and lungs. You will go to this center.
X-ray of paranasal sinuses: you can go to this center for an x-ray of the sinuses in your head. These are empty spaces made of bone that everyone has.
Bloodwork - Go to this lab and they will draw your blood.
tuberculin skin test - We will prick your skin and you will return in 2 days to check. If it gets big, it may mean that you have been exposed to tuberculosis. Have you ever received the bCG vaccine?
Sputum exam - we will take a swab of your nostrils and/or back of throat to check for X infection.
ECHO - We will refer you to a cardiology doctor to take a look at your heart’s function with an ultrasound
Bronchoscopy - We will refer you to a respirologist/ENT doctor to take a look inside your airways with a tube and camera.
ECG - Go to this lab to do ECG.

Supportive:
You can buy over-the-counter cough suppressants for a nocturnal dry cough.
Drink a lot of fluids.
Avoid transmission by wearing a mask, taking sick days as needed, and cleaning surfaces at home.

Allergies:
Avoid sleeping with pets.
Avoid exposure to environmental allergens.
Get over the counter nasal rinses and rinse your nose every night.
Take over-the-counter Benadryl or Cetirizine. Benadryl can make you sleepy.

Take these antibiotics for this many days. Take this many per day until you finish the course. Even if you get better, make sure to finish your full course. If your symptoms do not get better, please come back.
Short-acting inhalers: Take this puffer everytime you experience symptoms (like wheezing).
ICS: Take this puffer every day, ie in the morning. It will help your airways in the long term, so make sure you take it everyday
Chest physiotherapy: We will refer you to a physiotherapist to help clear out the mucus in your airways.
